 Ata Aidoo: An interview for ALT -- tREVIEWS -- tAmir Taj ElSir The Grub Hunter -- tGordon Collier. ed. Focus on Nigeria: Literature and Culture -- tDominique Chancé and Alain Ricard (eds). Études littéraires -- tLaura Murphy. Metaphor and the Slave Trade in West African Literature -- tEldred Durosimi Jones with Marjorie Jones. The Freetown Bond: A Life under Two Flags0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe success of the Caine Prize for African Writing and the growth of online publishing have played key roles in putting the short story in its rightful place within the study and criticism of African literature.African writers have, much more than the critics, recognized the beauty and potency of the short story. Always the least studied in African literature classrooms and the most critically overlooked genre in African literature today, the African short story is now given the attention it deserves. Contributors here take a close look at the African short story to re-define its own peculiar pedigree, chart its trajectory, critique its present state and examineits creative possibilities. They examine how the short story and the novel complement each other, or exist in contradistinction, within the context of culture and politics, history and public memory, legends, myths and folklore. Ernest Emenyonu is Professor of Africana Studies at the University of Michigan-Flint, USA; the editorial board is composed of scholars from US, UK and African universities Nigeria: HEBN  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aShort stories, African (English) -- History and criticism. 0aShort stories, African (English). 0aShort stories. 4aAfrican Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / African.2bisacsh  aAfrican Literature.  aCaine Prize.  aOnline Publishing.  a